Rating: 3
I modified this extensively to use what I had on hand. In lieu of green onions, I used yellow (at about 1/2 of the required amount, since around here they are SO hot). About tripled the bell peppers, as I had some home-grown that were not long for this world. Also added lots of chopped garlic to the sauté mixture. We like our food spicy, but since the veggies were so hot, I chose not to use Pepper Jack cheese, and subbed Kraft American Cheese Singles that I just laid on top of the bread layers. (Worried if this would make it soupy, but it turned out nice and firm.) Omitted the salt--it didn't need any. VERY, VERY GOOD. Next time I would cover the strata for the first 20 minutes, as mine did get a bit overly browned (almost burned). Very yummy as a casual dinner. Served it with a mandarin orange jell-o salad.

Rating: 3
I used sourdough bread and 2 percent milk, put in an extra egg, and let the strata sit overnight in the fridge before baking it. It had just the right amount of liquid when I did it that way. I think one of the great benefits of making a strata is that you CAN do it ahead of time and let it sit overnight. So I don't see the point of skipping that step.

